## Server vs Client Component Rules

{% if router == "app-router" %}
**Default: everything is a Server Component.** Add `"use client"` only when required.

| Situation | Server Component | Client Component |
|-----------|-----------------|-----------------|
| Fetch data from API / DB | YES | no |
| Read environment variables (secrets) | YES | no |
| Access request headers / cookies | YES | no |
| Use `useState`, `useReducer` | no | YES |
| Use `useEffect` | no | YES |
| Use browser APIs (`window`, `document`) | no | YES |
| Attach event listeners (`onClick`, `onChange`) | no | YES |
| Use third-party hooks | no | YES (usually) |
| Render other Server Components | YES | NO |

### Key rules

- **Never** use `useEffect` to fetch data in the App Router. Fetch in the Server Component directly.
- Keep Client Components as **leaf nodes** - push `"use client"` as far down the tree as possible.
- A Server Component can import and render a Client Component. The reverse is NOT possible.
- Pass data from Server to Client via props - not via a global store.

```tsx
// Correct pattern: Server Component fetches, Client Component handles interaction
// src/app/(dashboard)/products/[id]/page.tsx  (Server Component)
import { ProductDetailClient } from "@/components/features/products/ProductDetail.client";

export default async function ProductDetailPage({ params }) {
  const product = await getProduct(params.id); // server-side fetch
  return <ProductDetailClient product={product} />; // pass as prop
}

// src/components/features/products/ProductDetail.client.tsx
"use client";
export function ProductDetailClient({ product }: { product: Product }) {
  const [editing, setEditing] = useState(false); // client interactivity
  ...
}
```

{% else %}
In the Pages Router, all components are client-side by default. Use `getServerSideProps` or `getStaticProps` to fetch data server-side.

For expensive computations, use `getServerSideProps` rather than `useEffect` + `fetch` in a component.
{% endif %}

